deceiued you as you suppose, but none is deceiued so much as my
selfe: and if w=t= patience you will heare me, I will shew you:
At the same time y=t= I landed at Brist. there was one w=t= me,
that came out of Ireland also: a man y=t= seemed to be of good
credite, who had an Irish boy to waite vpon him, & hauing
bine as he said long out of England, bent his iourney to
visit his friends in Lancashire: we comming ouer both in one
ship, made accou~t also to lie in one lodging: & he hauing as
<P E2R>
well as my selfe good store of money, bought him selfe a new
sute of Apparell at Brist. the which in my eie seeming faire
& good, I woulde needes straight way buye me y=e= like, which
when I had done, I to haue the residue of my gold sure,
fearing eyther to be robed, or deceiued thereof, ript y=e= lineing of
my doublet in diuers places, & therein basted my gold most
secretly, now y=e= gentlma~ & I, lying together that night, the
next morning he rose before me, and as it seemed, he put on
my doublet & left me his: which I thinke on my conscience
he did it simplie & vnknowne to him selfe, because he made
himselfe ready in my sight, and at his departure away, he
brought me vp into my chamber a pinte of metheglin, and
drinkeing to me he bad me farewell: now I supposing all
this while y=t= I had my own doublet on, made indeede no
other reckning: had therein great store of golde, but when y=t=
this morning I searched & found it not so, you may thinke
that I was not a little [^SOURCE TEXT: liltle^] grieued: therefore   #
my masters here
